How to share data with a statistician

By Jeffrey Leek (@jtleek)

https://github.com/jtleek/datasharing

Topic outline

  • The raw data.
  • "A tidy data set is a standard way of mapping the meaning of a dataset to it's structure." (Wickham 2014)
  • A code book describing each variable and its values in the tidy data set.
  • An explicit and exact recipe you used to go from 1 -> 2,3

From: https://github.com/jtleek/datasharing/

What do we want to see?

3 T2 1 no 0
4 T3 22 maybe 3

What do we want to see?

mydatadescriptor <- read.delim("datadescriptor.csv", sep=",")
column description
ID unique sample identifier, a strictly increasing integer
C1 categorical, allowed values of T1, T2, and T3
C2 numerical (integer); missing values are blank
C3 categorical; yes, no, maybe, or N/A (cannot be measured)
C4 categorical; A, B; missing values are blank
notes free text notes
flag categorical, interestingness is 0,1,2, or 3

Teaching strategy - perfect world

I'd teach everyone

\(+\)

The Hadleyverse! (dplyr, reshape, ggplot2)

Teaching strategy - reality

Teach best practices in or slightly outside the Excel comfort zone, possibly working through an example.

Tidy data (0.5 hour)

Attendees should know:

  1. What is an un-tidy dataset?
  2. Why is a tidy dataset important?
  3. What do I do to make it tidy?

Data descriptors (0.5 hours)

Attendees should know:

  1. Why should I have separate data descriptors?
  2. What do I describe and how do I do it?
  3. How does this connect back to the data?

Applications/Interactive (0.5-1 hour(s))

  1. Metadata
  2. Data exploration
  3. Analysis
  4. etc…

A win for everyone!




If you don't…

You'll get emails from the statisticians, bioinformaticians, computational biologists, analysts, collaborators, and you have to do it anyways.
